04035nam a22006615i 9780271093390DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222002pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710933907 a10.1515/97802710933902doi  a(DE-B1597)617266  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBF1622b.J45 2002eb 7aHIS0020202bisacsh04a291.3/8/0932231 aJanowitz, Naomi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIcons of Power :bRitual Practices in Late Antiquity /cNaomi Janowitz. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMagic in History0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the waning years of the Roman Empire, Jews, Christians, and pagans alike used rituals to bridge the gap between the human and the divine. Depending on one’s point of view, however, such rituals could be labeled negatively as ";magic"; or positively as ";theurgy."; This has led to numerous problems of interpretation, including marginalizing certain ritual practices as magic or occult while privileging others as genuine or orthodox. In Icons of Power, Naomi Janowitz sifts through the polemics to make sense of the daunting mosaic of religious belief and practice in Late Antiquity. From rabbis who ascended to heavenly places, to sorcerers seeking to harm enemies with spells, to alchemists working metals to purify the soul, Janowitz reveals how ritual practitioners held common assumptions about why their rituals worked and about how to perform those rituals. Indeed, such assumptions were so much a part of the inherited mentality of the age that they were, for the most part, never explained—and this is precisely what Janowitz accomplishes in Icons of Power. By shifting the discussion out of the rhetoric of ";magic"; or ";mysticism"; and describing the mechanisms of ritual with semiotic terms, she moves us beyond the value-laden terminology of ancient polemicists and modern scholars so that we can better see how these rituals worked and how they affected the social identities of their followers. Janowitz recovers a lost world of religious expression that has been clouded by misinterpretation for many centuries. In the process, Icons of Power makes an important contribution to our understanding of society in Late Antiquity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aJewish magicxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMagic, Ancient. 0aRitualzRome. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271093390?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271093390423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271093390/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK